		<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>Lit Hub’s Most Anticipated Books of 2026, Part Two</h1>
		<h2>258 Books We're Looking Forward to Before the End of the Year</h2>	</div>
	</div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/"  title="Literary Hub">Literary Hub</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">July 1, 2026</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p>The year is half over, if you can believe it. Time marches ever forward, into the abyss. Books, though, can smooth the passage. If you choose wisely, that is. To that end, here are the novels, collections, and works of nonfiction we&#8217;re keeping an eye on for the rest of the year. Let us know what you&#8217;re looking forward to most in the comments.</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="color: #b23233;">JULY</span></strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="color: #b23233;">***</span></strong></h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264636" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/david-thomson-a-sudden-flicker-of-light/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light-.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="David Thomson, A Sudden Flicker of Light-" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--679x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264636" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--199x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light-.jpg 994w" alt="David Thomson, A Sudden Flicker of Light:" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="264636" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/david-thomson-a-sudden-flicker-of-light/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light-.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="David Thomson, A Sudden Flicker of Light-" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/David-Thomson-A-Sudden-Flicker-of-Light--679x1024.jpg" />David Thomson, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668205730" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>A Sudden Flicker of Light: A Revisionist History of Movies</em></a></strong><br />
Simon &amp; Schuster, July 7</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> David Thomson has been writing about film for fifty years, so when he argues (as he does in this book ) that  “movies have been a destructive force—responsible for creating an alternate reality and fantasyland that has only deepened the isolation and disconnection of our society over the course of a century,” I’m inclined to hear him out. (And not only because movies are too long to watch at night when I could be sleeping.)  <em>–Jessie Gaynor, Senior Editor</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="273162" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026-part-two/91j0erpkatl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/91J0erPKAtL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Emily Ruskovich, Nightjar" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/91J0erPKAtL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-273162" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/91J0erPKAtL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Emily Ruskovich, Nightjar" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/91J0erPKAtL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/91J0erPKAtL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/91J0erPKAtL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/91J0erPKAtL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />Emily Ruskovich, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780812994025" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Nightjar</em></a></strong><br />
Random House, July 7</h5>
<p>This debut short story collection from the International Dublin Literary Award-winning author of <em>Idaho</em> explores “how unexpected intuitions forever alter the lives of ordinary people.” Set against the lush, eerie backdrop of the Pacific Northwest, <em>Nightjar</em> includes the story “Owl”—about a fur trapper dealing with the terrible origins of his marriage after his wife is brutally injured by four teenage boys—which won an O. Henry Award in 2015. <em>–Dan Sheehan, Book Marks Editor-in-Chief</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264637" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/rachel-aviv-you-wont-get-free-of-it/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It-.jpg" data-orig-size="343,522" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Rachel Aviv, You Won&amp;#8217;t Get Free of It-" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It-.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264637" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It--197x300.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It--197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It--39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It--33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It-.jpg 343w" alt="Rachel Aviv, You Won't Get Free of It:" width="197" height="300" data-attachment-id="264637" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/rachel-aviv-you-wont-get-free-of-it/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It-.jpg" data-orig-size="343,522" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Rachel Aviv, You Won&amp;#8217;t Get Free of It-" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Rachel-Aviv-You-Wont-Get-Free-of-It-.jpg" />Rachel Aviv, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780525657057" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>You Won’t Get Free of It: Stories of Mothers and Daughters</em></a></strong><br />
Knopf, July 7</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> Rachel Aviv writes the kind of nonfiction that sucks you in and holds you long after you finish reading. Her last book, <em>Strangers to Ourselves</em>, was one of the most complex and illuminating works I’ve read in recent years. I’d be anticipating this one—which explores mother-daughter relationships—even if it didn’t speak so directly to me. As both a daughter and a mother of daughters, thought, I’m on the edge of my seat.  <em>–JG</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264639" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/christian-wiman-the-dance/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance.jpg" data-orig-size="978,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Christian Wiman, The Dance" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance-668x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264639" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance-196x300.jpg" alt="Christian Wiman, The Dance" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Christian-Wiman-The-Dance.jpg 978w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" />Christian Wiman, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374617400" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Dance</em></a></strong><br />
FSG, July 7</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> I love Christian Wiman’s poems and read them aloud whenever possible. Though his language is that of the every day his preternatural instinct for rhythm fills his lines with a bursting musicality. And though I am not, unlike Wiman, a man of faith, I share in his wonder of everyday holiness, for that ineluctable light that drags us from our solipsisms into a brighter way of being… even if only for a moment, even if for just the time it takes to read a poem.  –<em>Jonny Diamond, Editor-in-Chief</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264640" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/parini-shroff-some-people/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People.jpg" data-orig-size="987,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Parini Shroff, Some People" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People-674x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264640" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People-197x300.jpg" alt="Parini Shroff, Some People" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Parini-Shroff-Some-People.jpg 987w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" />Parini Shroff, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798217093670" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Some People</em></a></strong><br />
Algonquin, July 7</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> From the bestselling author of the delightful <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593498972" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Bandit Queens</em></a> comes a novel that sounds unbearably awkward and just as good: Malti Patel finds herself forced to recuperate for an entire week, under the care of her daughter&#8217;s soon to be ex-huband, Nathan. Clearly, both have resentments, and things to unpack, though they will, one supposes, also discover that they have at least one thing in common. Shroff is hilarious and winking and sharp but ultimately large-hearted; I think she will knock this premise out of the park. <em>–Emily Temple, Managing Editor</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264641" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/emeline-atwood-a-real-animal/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal.jpg" data-orig-size="993,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Emeline Atwood, A Real Animal" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal-678x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264641" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal-199x300.jpg" alt="Emeline Atwood, A Real Animal" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Emeline-Atwood-A-Real-Animal.jpg 993w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" />Emeline Atwood, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781646222964" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>A Real Animal</em></a></strong><br />
Catapult, July 7</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> I’d been hearing about this book through the grapevine for a long time before I got my hands on it, and once I did, I understood perfectly. This is a book that is a caliber above and beyond what we have come to expect from the young-twenties-girl-bildungsroman. There’s men, yes, and sex, a lot of it, and yearning to be understood, and for power and a place in the world, but <em>A Real Animal</em> is about the wild, deep, feral core of those themes. It’s about something subterranean, underneath one’s lived experience, underneath, even, one’s trauma. The book follows the protagonist from college, when she experiences a horrible sexual assault, through the next decade, as she builds and breaks relationships, as she builds and breaks a life. There is no straight line. There is no healing. But the book has this feeling about it, like there’s so much within the pages that’s just bursting to get out: a violent and powerful urge for something, for more survival, for more agency, to express one’s pain, to feel better. <em>A Real Animal</em> is as raw and visceral as an open-mouthed scream: you hear it in your bones. You can see its teeth. –<em>Julia Hass, Book Marks Associate Editor</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264642" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/shannon-sanders-the-great-wherever/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever.jpg" data-orig-size="987,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Shannon Sanders, The Great Wherever" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever-674x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264642" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever-197x300.jpg" alt="Shannon Sanders, The Great Wherever" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Shannon-Sanders-The-Great-Wherever.jpg 987w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" />Shannon Sanders, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250421678" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Great Wherever</em></a></strong><br />
Henry Holt, July 7</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> This book circles one of my favorite riddles for fiction: how do we carry ancestral expectations? When Audrey Lamb, an underpaid gig worker in D.C., inherits family farmland in Tennessee, she goes to claim her birthright—only to discover the property is ruled by four familial ghosts. An epic with supernatural and epigenetic overtones, this debut novel looks like a feast of a story.  <em>–Brittany Allen, Staff Writer</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264643" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/daniel-mason-country-people/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People.jpg" data-orig-size="1011,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Daniel Mason, Country People" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People-690x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264643" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People-202x300.jpg" alt="Daniel Mason, Country People" width="202" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People-202x300.jpg 202w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People-690x1024.jpg 690w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People-768x1139.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Daniel-Mason-Country-People.jpg 1011w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 202px) 100vw, 202px" />Daniel Mason, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798217197453" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Country People</em></a></strong><br />
Random House, July 14</h5>
<p>The question of how one could possibly follow up <em>North Woods</em> would be a real, pressing conundrum: the bestselling novel from 2023 felt as though it sprang directly from the earth itself, like a story that had been lying dormant, waiting to be told for centuries, until it finally found the way to emerge. But emerge it did, through Daniel Mason’s talents and intellect, and with that, he has earned our trust in all perpetuity. <em>Country People</em> is, albeit, a far more human tale: a (somewhat) realist novel about a family as they embark on a new chapter together in a faraway land totally unlike their accustomed surroundings. That is, Vermont, to their native California. It’s a roving and fairy-tale like story, told through the gaze of an idealist, though career-stymied, father as he raises his children, loves his wife, struggles through his ambitions, and finds solace in the unusual lives of his new eccentric neighbors, the “country people” themselves. Mason’s prose is as fantastic as ever, and it’s a treat to experience the magic in everyday life through his narrator’s rosy and ever curious gaze. –<em>JH</em></p>
