><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063437937" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Everything to the Sea</a></em></strong><br />
William Morrow, July 14</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> This debut novel hinges on an epic premise. In Hawai’i, two lovers (Kenji and Jane) are drawn together for what’s supposed to be a summer fling. But when a tsunami rocks their island, profound tragedy ensues, and immediately ups the stakes of a brief encounter. This big-souled book considers the costs of leaving and staying, especially where rebuilding is required. Upano’s operatic scope and clean, elegant sentences really swept me off my feet.  <em>–BA</em></p>
