br />
Riverhead, July 21</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/19-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our summer reading list:</em></a> Nobody writes about the Mojave like Claire Vaye Watkins. The author of <em>Battleborn</em> and <em>I Love You But I’ve Chosen Darkness</em> returns to the cosmic high desert with a story about a Sierra Club fundraiser and aspiring activist—on the cusp of her fortieth birthday—who decides that she wants another child. With a young daughter at school back East, a motley crew of eco warrior pals in her corner, and a long-lost love returned but not ready for fatherhood, Rose embarks upon a novel (and liberating) conception quest while contemplating the doomed majesty of her desert home. A wild, lush, lyrical, torrent of novel—both ode and elegy—that left me reeling. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="273166" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026-part-two/attachment/9798217198337/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/9798217198337.jpg" data-orig-size="300,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Michael Cunningham, Unsayable" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/9798217198337.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-273166" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/9798217198337-200x300.jpg" alt="Michael Cunningham, Unsayable" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/9798217198337-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/9798217198337-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/9798217198337-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/9798217198337.jpg 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />Michael Cunningham, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798217198337" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Unsayable</em></a></strong><br />
Random House July 21</h5>
<p>This intimate memoir from the Pulitzer Prize-winning author of <em>The Hours</em> considers a life devoted to the practice of writing fiction. Cunningham plucks small, formative autobiographical moments from decades past and considers how each helped shape the writer, and the man, he became. A quiet, contemplative book about trying to put into words the ineffable experience of living. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="273167" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026-part-two/71mzue1nbyl-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/71mZUE1NByL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="714,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kohei Saito, tr. Brian Bergstrom, Capital from Zero" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/71mZUE1NByL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-273167" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/71mZUE1NByL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-214x300.jpg" alt="Kohei Saito, tr. Brian Bergstrom, Capital from Zero" width="214" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/71mZUE1NByL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-214x300.jpg 214w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/71mZUE1NByL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-43x60.jpg 43w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/71mZUE1NByL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-36x50.jpg 36w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/71mZUE1NByL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 714w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 214px) 100vw, 214px" />Kohei Saito, tr. Brian Bergstrom, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662603419" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Capital from Zero: Reading Marx in the Age of Climate Catastrophe</em> </a></strong><br />
Astra House, July 21</h5>
<p>Philosopher Saitō brings a pragmatic, eco-socialist’s approach to the problem of climate collapse and its inextricable connection to modern capitalism. Unsurprisingly the thinker behind “degrowth communism” excavates (and reconstitutes) aspects of Marx’s 19th-century ideas as solutions for 21st-century disaster. <em>–JD</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="264651" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/valeria-luiselli-beginning-middle-end/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Valeria Luiselli, Beginning Middle End" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-264651" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End-200x300.jpg" alt="Valeria Luiselli, Beginning Middle End" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Valeria-Luiselli-Beginning-Middle-End.jpg 1000w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />Valeria Luiselli, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798217208319" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Beginning Middle End</em></a></strong><br />
Knopf, July 28</h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026/?single=true" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As highlighted in our first half preview:</em></a> A mother-daughter duo land in Sicily after the collapse of the former’s marriage, setting off an exploration of their own family line as well as the possibilities (and pitfalls) of a changing world. Luiselli is one of the writers pushing fiction forward and wherever she goes, we would do well to follow.<em>  –DB</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="273695" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026-part-two/jan-carson-few-and-far-between/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between.jpg" data-orig-size="800,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Jan Carson, Few and Far Between" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-273695" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between-200x300.jpg" alt="Jan Carson, Few and Far Between" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Jan-Carson-Few-and-Far-Between.jpg 800w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />Jan Carson, </strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668056639" class="external" target="_blank"><strong><em>Few and Far Between</em></strong></a><strong><br />
</strong>Scribner, July 28</h5>
<p>The new novel from the EU Prize for Literature-winning Belfast author Carson (<em>The Raptures</em>, <em>Quickly While They Still Have Horses</em>) has a fascinating premise: in an alternate north of Ireland, a group of people looking to escape the dangers of the Troubles established a utopian community within a drained Lough Neagh (the largest lake in Ireland). Decades later, the few remaining inhabitants of “The Ark” must contend with algae outbreak that is slowly destroying the landscape they love, and government plans to force them back to the mainland for the first time in fifty years. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="273168" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2026-part-two/attachment/1509567828/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/1509567828.jpg" data-orig-size="300,452" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Anja Zimmermann, tr. Nicola Barfoot, The Breast" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/1509567828.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-273168" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/1509567828-199x300.jpg" alt="Anja Zimmermann, tr. Nicola Barfoot, The Breast" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/1509567828-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/1509567828-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/1509567828.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/1509567828-33x50.jpg 33w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" />Anja Zimmermann, tr. Nicola Barfoot, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781509567829" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Breast: A Cultural and Political History</em> </a></strong><br />
Polity, July 28</h5>
<p>Boobs are a rich text, so I’m optimistic that art historian Anja Zimmerman’s exploration of the social and political construction of The Breast will be a fascinating read, and will arm me with enough interesting tit facts to make me absolutely insufferable at parties. <em>–JG</em></p>
